# API Layer Conventions

## Structure
All backend calls are centralised in `lib/api/`:

```
lib/api/
  api.gateway.ts        ← Axios client + interceptors (do not modify unless necessary)
  api.route.ts          ← Aggregates all route files
  routes/
    public.route.ts     ← Unauthenticated endpoints (/pub/*)
    admin.route.ts      ← Admin endpoints (/admin/*)
    fc.route.ts         ← FC portal endpoints (/fc/*)
    user.route.ts       ← Authenticated user endpoints (/user/*)
```

## Adding a New Endpoint
1. Add the function to the correct route file (grouped into a const API object, e.g. `productAPI`, `newsAPI`).
2. Export it via the section's route aggregator object at the bottom of the file.
3. Do **not** make `axios` calls directly in components or pages — always go through the route files.

```ts
// lib/api/routes/admin.route.ts
const newsAPI = {
  getNews: (page: number, pageSize: number) =>
    api.get<NewsResponse>(`/admin/news`, { params: { page, pageSize } }),
};

export const adminRoutes = {
  news: newsAPI,
  // ...
};
```

## Using the API in Components
```ts
import { apiRoutes } from "@/lib/api/api.route";

// In a React Query hook
const { data } = useQuery({
  queryKey: ["news", page],
  queryFn: () => apiRoutes.admin.news.getNews(page, 10),
});
```

## Typing Pattern
Always provide both payload type `T` and response type `R`:
```ts
api.post<CreateRequest, CreateResponse>("/admin/products", data)
api.get<ProductListResponse>("/admin/products", { params })
api.put<UpdateRequest, UpdateResponse>(`/admin/products/${id}`, data)
api.patch<StatusPayload, StatusResponse>("/admin/products/status", payload)
api.delete<ApiResponse<null>>(`/admin/products/${id}`)
```

## Error Handling
The gateway automatically:
- Attaches the Bearer token from cookies
- Redirects to `/login` on 401/403 responses

In components, catch `ApiError` for user-facing messages:
```ts
import { ApiError } from "@/lib/api/api.gateway";

try {
  await apiRoutes.admin.news.createNews(payload);
} catch (error) {
  if (error instanceof ApiError) {
    toast.error(error.message);
  }
}
```

## File Uploads
Use `putObjects` from `lib/api/aws/putObjects.ts` to upload files to S3 first, then save the returned URL to the backend:
```ts
import { putObjects, Photo } from "@/lib/api/aws/putObjects";

const photos: Photo[] = files.map(file => ({ id: Date.now(), file, imgUrl: "" }));
const uploaded = await putObjects(`products/${productId}`, photos);
// uploaded[n].imgUrl contains the S3 URL
```
